[t06] │     "/01_capture/influential/2026-02-10__how-i-use-claude-code.md": "# How I Use Claude Code\n\n- **Source URL:** https://boristane.com/blog/how-i-use-claude-code/\n- **Captured for this template on:** 2026-02-10\n- **Why keep this:** it is a practical operator write-up about how to use a coding agent without giving up design control\n\n## Raw notes\n\n- Separate research, planning, and implementation instead of jumping straight to code.\n- Keep the plan as a persistent markdown artifact and review it before any code is written.\n- Use short implementation feedback only after the design work has already been resolved in the plan.\n- Narrow scope aggressively after a bad run instead of trying to salvage every wrong direction.\n\n<!-- AIOS-NOTE: This is a good beginner source because it gives John a workflow, not just opinions about tools. -->\n",
[t06] │     "/01_capture/influential/2026-02-15__openai-harness-engineering.md": "# OpenAI: harness engineering\n\n- **Source URL:** https://openai.com/index/harness-engineering/\n- **Archive URL:** https://web.archive.org/web/20260212020647id_/https://openai.com/index/harness-engineering/\n- **Captured for this template on:** 2026-02-15\n- **Why keep this:** it is one of the clearest public descriptions of agent-first software delivery\n\n## Raw notes\n\n- The reported leverage comes from humans designing the environment, constraints, and feedback loops while agents execute.\n- As throughput rises, review bandwidth becomes the scarce resource.\n- Repository knowledge needs to be structured and inspectable by the agent, not buried in one giant instruction file.\n- Mechanical boundaries, custom lints, and structural tests act as speed multipliers in agent-heavy systems.\n\n<!-- AIOS-NOTE: This is the strongest “org design shifts when coding is delegated” source in the starter pack. -->\n",
[t06] │     "/01_capture/influential/2026-03-06__anthropic-biology-of-llms.md": "# Anthropic: On the Biology of a Large Language Model\n\n- **Source URL:** https://www.anthropic.com/research/biology-of-a-large-language-model\n- **Captured for this template on:** 2026-03-06\n- **Why keep this:** it broadens AI engineering beyond prompts and agents into debugging and failure analysis\n\n## Raw notes\n\n- Anthropic treats surprising model behavior as something that can sometimes be localized and studied, not only measured from outputs.\n- Interpretability is most useful when the same class of failure keeps repeating and black-box mitigation stops helping.\n- This suggests a practical engineering ladder: catch failures with evals first, escalate to deeper inspection only when the failure class is persistent or high-stakes.\n- Good operational traces and eval artifacts make future debugging work more valuable.\n\n<!-- AIOS-NOTE: For John's repo, interpretability should be framed as an escalation path after ordinary eval and tooling work, not as the default starting point. -->\n",
[t06] │     "/01_capture/influential/2026-03-17__intercom-claude-code-platform.md": "# Intercom: Claude Code as an internal platform\n\n- **Source URL:** https://x.com/brian_scanlan/status/2033978300003987527\n- **Mirror URL:** https://twitter-thread.com/t/2033978300003987527\n- **Captured for this template on:** 2026-03-17\n- **Why keep this:** it is a concrete example of how coding assistants become governed internal infrastructure\n\n## Raw notes\n\n- Intercom describes a managed Claude Code platform with plugins, skills, hooks, telemetry, and controlled rollout.\n- The standout example is a read-only production console behind MCP with strong safety gates and auditing.\n- Session telemetry and transcript analysis feed directly into new skills and better defaults.\n- The same platform is used beyond engineers, which implies the packaging and policy layers matter as much as the model.\n\n<!-- AIOS-NOTE: The compounding asset here is the improvement loop from real sessions to new skills and safer defaults. -->\n",
[t06] │     "/01_capture/influential/2026-03-23__hn-structured-outputs-practical-notes.md": "# Hacker News notes: structured outputs need schema design and evals\n\n- **HN discussion:** [Sampling and structured outputs in LLMs](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=45345207)\n- **Related comments:** [property ordering gotcha](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=45347100), [error-tolerant parsing discussion](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=45347840)\n- **Captured on:** 2026-03-23\n- **Why keep this:** it adds practitioner friction that polished vendor docs usually skip\n\n## Raw notes\n\n- Structured outputs are useful, but they do not remove the need for validation and evals.\n- Schema details can change behavior more than people expect; field ordering and nested object shape can affect generation quality.\n- Some teams prefer error-tolerant parsing over hard constrained decoding, especially when they want reasoning-rich outputs.\n- The practical engineering question is not “structured or unstructured,” but which failure mode is easier to observe and repair in your system.\n\n<!-- AIOS-NOTE: This is useful because it turns structured outputs from a marketing checkbox into a design tradeoff. -->\n",
