--- /01_notes/canalport-shipping.md ---
# CanalPort Shipping

## Journal

CanalPort Shipping came from a port operations referral and the value case was obvious because the team was already drowning in manual exception tracking. The deal closed when the rollout was narrowed into something operationally safe instead of trying to fix every workflow at once.

The pain is real, but urgency stays medium because they can still absorb a lot through overtime and informal heroics. That means progress usually comes from reducing one recurring mess, not from grand transformation talk.

## Collaboration ideas

- Offer a phased review of dispatch exceptions and customer update workflows.
- Package a service around customs paperwork coordination and operational follow-through.
- Keep any proposal narrow enough that the buyer can say yes without re-litigating the whole program.

## Synergy ideas

- CanalPort Shipping could be networked with GreenGrid Energy around operational control-room habits: both have regional coordination problems where the real win is fewer dropped exceptions, not prettier reporting.
- There may also be a practical angle with Acme Logistics if CanalPort wants to compare how another logistics account frames phased rollout and warehouse-side exception handling.


============================================================
--- /01_notes/greengrid-energy.md ---
# GreenGrid Energy

## Journal

GreenGrid Energy came through an advisor introduction and the early traction came from field operations pain, not from top-down strategy. The team saw enough waste in site-level issue follow-up to approve an initial subscription before budget windows closed, which is usually a good sign that the problem is tangible.

The account has responsive champions, but the next step still needs a careful business case. They are interested, just not loose with new budget.

## Collaboration ideas

- Offer a working session on site-level issue tracking and regional operator follow-up.
- Bring a compact business case tied to time saved and fewer dropped follow-ups.
- Keep expansion ideas operational and measurable rather than visionary.

## Synergy ideas

- GreenGrid Energy and CanalPort Shipping could be a credible peer-to-peer conversation because both teams deal with distributed operations, exception handling, and too much manual coordination under time pressure.
- If GreenGrid wants proof that a narrow rollout can still work, reference Acme Robotics as another account that responded better to one concrete workflow fix than to broad transformation language.


